n of a Confucian orthodoxy during the imperial era, and the establishment of a Chinese philosophy in the Republic. This volume adopts a historical approach, tracing the most important portrayals of Yang Zhu in their own contexts and mutual connections. It yields new insights not only into the figure of Yang Zhu, but also into the stages of China's intellectual history. Scarcity of reliable textual support is, to varying degrees, a common predicament in the study of ancient Chinese masters, but the case of Yang Zhu is particularly illuminating. The remarkable dearth of textual material represents the almost "nothing" out of which early Chinese philosophers such as Yang Zhu have been fruitfully "created."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Confucianism. 4aHistory : History. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Taoism. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aBrindley, Erica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCao, Feng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChang, Yao-cheng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDefoort, Carine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDefoort, Carine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKlein, Esther Sunkyung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Ting-mien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Ting-mien, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLin, Xiaoqing Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMakeham, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSato, Masayuki, econtributor.4ctb4https:/